{
  "name": "Seven-Point Story Structure",
  "advantages": [
    "More straightforward and organized than traditional three-act structure while maintaining similar effectiveness",
    "Applicable to any genre including romance, sci-fi, and other story types",
    "Creates better story flow that is easier for readers to absorb and follow",
    "Ideal for authors who have created an intriguing protagonist but need a narrative structure to fit them in",
    "Provides a newer mental model for creating exciting stories that ignore traditional status quo approaches"
  ],
  "disadvantages": [
    "The term 'Hook' can confuse writers because this section can include more than just a hook, unlike other structures that use more open-ended names",
    "The 'Resolution' section problematically combines both climax and falling action together when they should ideally be split into separate sections"
  ],
  "elements": [
    {
      "name": "The Hook",
      "description": "Introduce the protagonist and their environment to pique reader interest. Show a sample of events the main character will face before the real story begins. This section establishes the character's normal world and gives readers enough information to want to continue reading.",
      "relative_length": 15,
      "examples": [
        "Rocky Balboa is a struggling boxer past his prime and having financial troubles. He has the potential to be a champion but doesn't believe he has the skills to compete against quality fighters. Part of him feels like all he needs is a chance to show he can be successful and someone to support him because he's never had anyone care about him."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Plot Point 1",
      "description": "Present an odd or surprising inciting incident that kick-starts the main story. This event pushes the main character outside their uneventful existence and pulls them into the heart of the story. The goal is to help the story pick up steam and momentum in the character's world.",
      "relative_length": 10,
      "examples": [
        "Apollo Creed, the current heavyweight champion, had a championship bout scheduled, but the contender was injured and had to cancel. Apollo comes up with an idea to find a fighter last minute but still gets the fans excited to see the fight. He gives Rocky a chance even though he's a nobody in the sport as a publicity stunt and because he thinks the match will be easy."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Pinch Point 1",
      "description": "Introduce the story's equivalent of pain points where the protagonist discovers their purpose mid-journey. An antagonistic character or occurrence enters the narrative and initiates conflict. Focus on creating interesting antagonistic forces that provide solid opposition to the protagonist.",
      "relative_length": 15,
      "examples": [
        "After Rocky gets the news that he will get a shot at the championship title, he starts to feel the pressure. Between his lack of confidence and the environment he was raised in holding him back, the chances of a victory seem low."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Midpoint",
      "description": "Show the main character transitioning from observing to taking action. The character stops being reactive and becomes proactive with a clear goal in mind. They now know what needs to be done to achieve their objective and begin making concrete steps toward that goal.",
      "relative_length": 20,
      "examples": [
        "Rocky decides to take action and go from reactive to proactive. He asks Mickey, the local gym owner, to be his trainer and begins to wake up every morning to train with him. He stops all the bad habits that were getting in the way of his success."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Pinch Point 2",
      "description": "Present the main character's lowest point where they hit rock bottom and almost lose hope. This is where story leads take time to recuperate after getting hurt. The character faces their darkest moment before the final push toward resolution.",
      "relative_length": 15,
      "examples": [
        "Rocky's antagonistic forces come back to haunt him once again before his big fight. The evening before the boxing match, he begins to lose his confidence again and questions if he deserves the opportunity when others are more deserving. Instead of setting a goal to win the bout, he decides the best he can do is go the distance and not get knocked out."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Plot Point 2",
      "description": "Show when the main character finds what they need to move toward completing their goal or finding a solution. This discovery may not always lead to a cheerful ending, but it provides the key element needed for the story's resolution. The character gains crucial insight or resources for the final confrontation.",
      "relative_length": 10,
      "examples": [
        "Right when the viewers begin to think Rocky doesn't have a chance, he knocks Apollo Creed down for the first time in his career, and the plot takes a turn for the better. But it's only the first round, and Rocky has another 14 to go to prove he can stand toe to toe with a world champion."
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Resolution",
      "description": "Bring all significant plot points to an end and solve outstanding conflicts. The protagonist may or may not achieve their objective - some stories end in tragedy while others end happily. Show the results of the character's journey and the consequences of their actions throughout the story.",
      "relative_length": 15,
      "examples": [
        "Towards the end of the final fight, you can see the work he put in during the midpoint starting to pay off. The resolution shows Rocky achieving his goal of making it through the entire fight without giving up. Some readers might even consider that he won, but the match is a draw for the time being."
      ]
    }
  ]
}
